<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Enable Quality Metrics on Splunk Observability Cloud Workshops</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/en/ninja-workshops/ai/4-splunk-agent-observability/6-enable-metrics/</link><description>Recent content in Enable Quality Metrics on Splunk Observability Cloud Workshops</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><atom:link href="https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/en/ninja-workshops/ai/4-splunk-agent-observability/6-enable-metrics/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Enable Metrics on the Log Stream</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/en/ninja-workshops/ai/4-splunk-agent-observability/6-enable-metrics/1-enable-metrics/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/en/ninja-workshops/ai/4-splunk-agent-observability/6-enable-metrics/1-enable-metrics/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Metrics are configured on the &lt;strong&gt;log stream&lt;/strong&gt;, so every new trace that lands is scored
automatically. You&amp;rsquo;ll turn on a set of out-of-the-box metrics that matter for a healthcare
assistant.&lt;/p&gt;
